context: In the <a4_0>fifth century<a4_0/> Strasbourg was occupied successively by Alemanni, Huns, and Franks. In the ninth century it was commonly known as <a3_0>Strazburg<a3_0/> in the local language, as documented in <b6_0><b8_0>842<b8_0/><b6_0/> by the Oaths of Strasbourg. This trilingual text contains, alongside texts in Latin and Old High German (<b9_0>teudisca lingua<b9_0/>), the oldest written variety of Gallo-Romance (<b7_0>lingua romana<b7_0/>) clearly distinct from Latin, the ancestor of Old French. The town was also called Stratisburgum or Strateburgus in Latin, from which later came Strossburi in <a1_0>Alsatian<a1_0/> and <a2_0>Straßburg<a2_0/> in Standard German, and then Strasbourg in French. The Oaths of Strasbourg is considered as marking the birth of the two countries of <b5_0>France and Germany<b5_0/> with the division of the <a0_0>Carolingian Empire<a0_0/>.
